{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox Australian place | type = protected | name = Coombabah Lake Conservation Park | state = qld | iucn_category = III | image = | caption = | image_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|27|54|34|S|153|21|7|E|scale:250|display=inline,title}} | force_national_map = | relief = yes | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | map_alt = | nearest_town_or_city = Brisbane | area = {{convert|1959|ha|abbr=on}}<!-- If the area is greater than 100ha (1km2) a conversion template is not required. --> | area_footnotes = <ref name=DOIW/> | established = {{start date|1997}} | established_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.protectedplanet.net/sites/Coombabah_Lake_Conservation_Park|title=Coombabah Lake Conservation Park|work=protectedplanet.net|publisher= |date=1997|accessdate=27 June 2014 }}</ref> | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_footnotes = | managing_authorities = {{unbulleted list|[[Gold Coast City Council]] {{small|(tourism)}}|Queensland National Parks and Wildlife Service {{small|(national and marine parks)}}|Department of Primary Industries and Fisheries {{small|(fish habitat areas and intertidal zones)}}|Department of Transport {{small|(marine infrastructure and passageways)}}|Department of Natural Resources and Mines {{small|waterways and leased land)}}|Environmental Protection Agency {{small|(sewerage treatment plant licenses, pollution issues, coastal plans, dredging licenses, and the [[List of Ramsar sites in Australia#Wetlands in Queensland|Ramsar]] area)}}}} | url = www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/wetlands/report.pl?smode=DOIW&doiw_refcodelist=QLD194 <!-- Deprecated parameters --> <!-- The following parameters have been deprecated since 27 December 2013. This infobox should be modified so that these parameters are no longer needed. --> }} The '''Coombabah Lake Conservation Park''' is a [[nature reserve|conservation park]] that is an [[A Directory of Important Wetlands in Australia|Important Wetland in Australia]], located in the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] region of [[South East Queensland]], [[Australia]]. Part of the [[Coomera River]] [[drainage basin|catchment]], Lake Coombabah is a tidal [[lake]] at the [[mouth (river)|mouth]] of Coombabah Creek. The Coombabah wetlands are significant because they are the most southerly lake and coastal swampland representatives in the bioregion, and because the area provides significant wildlife value and refuge habitat.<ref name=DOIW>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/wetlands/report.pl?smode=DOIW&doiw_refcodelist=QLD194|title=Lake Coombabah - QLD194|work=Directory of Important Wetlands in Australia - Information sheet|publisher=[[Department of the Environment (Australia)|Department of the Environment]], [[Australian Government]]|date=10 May 2010 |accessdate=27 June 2014 }}</ref> The conservation area includes tidal marshlands and mangroves along part of the lakes edge. The Melaleuca boardwalk allows viewing of the wildlife. The mangroves are home to frogs, crabs and fish that attract native and migratory birds. There are guided bushwalking and canoeing activities as part of community conservation and environmental workshops to promote local conservation.<ref name=GCCC/>
==Location and features== Situated near the suburb of {{QLDcity|Coombabah}}, {{convert|5|km}} from the coast and {{convert|8|km}} northwest of {{QLDcity|Southport}}, the lake borders the Ivan Gibbs Wetland Reserve, is classified as a Fish Habitat Area within the [[Moreton Bay Marine Park]] and serves as an important wildlife corridor between the Nerang State Forest and the coast.<ref name=GCCC>{{cite web|title=Coombabah Lakes Conservation Area|url=http://www.gcparks.com.au/park-details.aspx?park=175|work=Tourism: Parks|publisher=[[Gold Coast City Council]]|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>
The lake is fed by Coombabah Creek which rises to the west in the Nerang Forest Reserve. The Ivan Gibbs Wetlands Reserve and Lakeside Country Club golf course are both located to the south of the lake. Houses in [[Helensvale, Queensland|Helensvale]] have been built a short distance from the lake's western shore.
